Russian President Vladimir Putin has signed a law on the introduction of administrative liability for violation of the term and procedure for payment of goods (works, services) in procurement for state and municipal needs.
This law is intended to solve the very acute problem of non-compliance by customers in state and municipal procurement.
As recently as two years ago, the situation where entrepreneurs could not get paid on already executed state and municipal contracts was widespread.
At the same time, the president of Russia instructed the Prosecutor General's Office of the Russian Federation to take special control of the problem.
Because businessmen themselves could not cope with unscrupulous customers who entered into unfunded contracts, tried in every way to evade their obligations to pay and included illegal conditions in the contracts.
The problem was systemic in the country as a whole.
Since 2015, in order to protect the rights of entrepreneurs to receive payment on public orders, the Prosecutor's Office has made 9.7 thousand submissions, as a result of their consideration, 4.5 thousand officials have been disciplined, 533 administrative officials have been prosecuted, 75 materials have been submitted to the investigative bodies for the organization of procedural inspections, and 46 of them have been prosecuted.
As a result, the debt to entrepreneurs in the amount of more than 66 billion rubles was repaid.
And these huge sums were not accumulated as a result of non-payment of multibillion-dollar contracts.
Numerous, systematic delays in the payment of services to entrepreneurs for much more modest amounts have led to huge debts.
Here is a typical case.
The head of a small company won a competition for the provision of social transportation services for several million rubles.
The person invested all his working capital, fully fulfilled the obligations, but did not receive the money in time.
The result is an escalating financial pile of debts on salaries, taxes, loans, which would lead to bankruptcy if the entrepreneur did not seek help from the prosecutor's office.
The problem has now been reduced as much as possible in a number of regions.
Nevertheless, as of the first half of 2017, the total amount of debt under state and municipal contracts, revealed by prosecutors of the constituent entities of the Russian Federation, amounted to about 27.4 billion rubles.
In regions where debt indicators continue to reach critical values, the Prosecutor's Office operates in manual crisis management mode.
The Prosecutor General personally holds visiting meetings with representatives of the local authority, at which all violations uncovered by prosecutors and measures to eliminate them immediately are dealt with.
Such operational meetings this year have already been held in Yaroslavl and Yekaterinburg.
The implementation of Federal Law No. 189-FZ "on amendments to the Code of Administrative Offences of the Russian Federation in terms of establishing administrative liability of the officials of the customer for violation of the term and procedure for payment of goods (works, services) in procurement for state and municipal needs," which was signed last week by the President of Russia, will be able to improve the payment discipline of public customers.
The draft law was developed by the Ministry of Economic Development of Russia on the initiative of the Prosecutor General's Office.
The new law will supplement the Code of Administrative Offences of the Russian Federation with an article that provides for a fine of 30 thousand to 50 thousand rubles for violation by the official of the customer of the term and procedure for payment of goods, works and services in state and municipal procurement.
And if the official has already been subjected to administrative punishment for a similar offence, he will be disqualified for a period of one to two years.
All prosecutors of the constituent entities of the Russian Federation have already been instructed to ensure the application of these legislative innovations in practice.
Civil rights group announces travel warning in Missouri
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People issued a warning to people of color traveling to Missouri because of discriminatory state policies and racist attacks.
The group's statement reads: "The warning to the traveling National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, valid until August 28, 2017, calls on African-American travelers, visitors and Missouri citizens to be particularly attentive and to exercise increased caution when traveling around the state in connection with a number of questionable racist incidents that have recently occurred throughout the state and are cited here."
According to the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, the announcement of a travel warning by the group prompted a recent Missouri law that made it harder for people to win discrimination claims, as well as the fact that state law enforcement agencies disproportionately chose minorities as their targets.
"You have people who are subjected to human rights violations.
They are stopped on the roads because of the color of their skin, they are beaten and killed, "Rod Chapel, President of the Missouri National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, told the Kansas City Star newspaper.
"We hear complaints often like never before."
This is the first warning of its kind announced by the organization in relation to the state of the United States.
The group referred to incidents such as the racial humiliation of black students at the University of Missouri and the death of twenty-seven-year-old Tory Sanders, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died in suspicious circumstances earlier this year after running out of gasoline while traveling around the state, and Missouri state police arrested him without charging him with a crime.
The warning also mentions a recent report by the Missouri Attorney General's office, according to which black drivers are 75 percent more likely to be stopped on the road than white drivers.
"The purpose of the warning is for people to be aware of the situation and alert their relatives and friends and colleagues about what could happen in Missouri," Chapel said.
"People should be prepared in one way or another, whether they will take money with them for bail or tell relatives that they are traveling in the state."
According to the latest data from the FBI's hate crime reporting program, there were 100 hate crimes reported in Missouri in 2015, making the state sixteenth in the state in terms of the number of such violations.
The travel warning is also a response to a new Missouri law that will make it more difficult to bring a case against a legal entity for housing or labor discrimination.
Earlier, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) announced warnings for travelers to Texas and Arizona after those states passed new immigration control laws ordering local law enforcement agencies to arrest people for violating immigration laws, which the ACLU said should have increased the number of racial checks.
Travel warnings are usually issued by the State Department for other countries, but recently public organizations have resorted to this measure in response to certain laws and trends within the United States.
