When preparing lunch, Bardina Degey does not use the stove.
She even uses a pot rarely.
In her wooden house in Enarotali, the capital of Paniai County in the rebel Indonesian province of Papua, the housewife usually simply places the sweet potato, which here is called the "note," directly into the hotbed.
Half an hour later, the charred tuber is taken out and eaten with impatient, unwashed hands.
Degey sits on the ground floor - she has no furniture - and this is where she does her housework, such as washing clothes with muddy water from a nearby swamp.
The toilet serves as a bucket in a room without a roof.
She is the youngest of her husband's four wives, so she was not assigned to work in the field.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, it can be dangerous to work late: many men from this village are unemployed, many drink, and there are soldiers.
"No one decides to walk around the village after 5pm," she says.
This is a rare opportunity to look at daily life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was annexed to Indonesia in 1969 after a dubious referendum, when only 1,026 elders were forced to vote, raising their hands in front of occupying troops.
The existing pro-independence movement from the Netherlands quickly turned its anger against the government of Jakarta, which maintains tight control over the region, preventing foreign journalists and human rights activists.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, and the Independent State of Papua New Guinea occupies the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is a city as remote as it is abandoned; the road here includes a one-and-a-half-hour flight from Jayapura, the administrative center of the Province, to Nabir, and then a five-hour rag on a car.
There is no public transport here.
The city, with a population of about 19,000, consists of wooden houses lined with bamboo fences; the roofs of corrugated steel are painted with rust in a variety of red-faced shades.
Few Indonesians, let alone journalists, and almost none of the foreigners, got here.
Prior to the arrival of the Christian missionaries, the Papuan Mee Pago worshiped a god named UGA tameye.
There have been other changes.
"It was unusual for us to wear these clothes," Degey says, gesturing at his bright, hand-woven turban, dark skirt and bright shirt.
"We used to wear only leaves on the body."
Papua is Indonesia's poorest province, with 28% of its population living below the poverty line, and infant mortality and literacy rates among the worst in Asia.
But it is also Indonesian gold land.
The world's largest and most profitable gold mine, Grasberg, owned by Phoenix-based Freeport McMoran, is just sixty miles from Paniai, a highland province about the size of New Jersey where 153,000 people live.
In 2015 alone, Freeport produced approximately $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper.
In addition, Papua boasts an estimated $78 billion worth of forest reserves.
These riches, however, entail one misfortune for Papuans, ensuring that Indonesia's powerful armed forces maintain their suffocating presence here.
According to an investigation by the New York Times in 2005, between 1998 and 2004, Freeport paid nearly $20 million to local troops and units, including up to $150,000 to one officer.
Demands for greater autonomy on the part of Papuans threaten the existence of this golden vest and are ruthlessly suppressed.
According to human rights defenders, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed by Indonesian military forces since 1969, and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned.
According to the Asian Human Rights Commission, massacres in the indigenous highlands of Papua in the Seventies could be considered genocide.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
"We will lose everything," a report published in 2016 by the Brisbane diocese, contains evidence of atrocities committed in the previous year, such as summary executions, torture - particularly frequent, as claimed in another report, rape and electric shocks - and the brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrations.
"It's hard to count the number of victims because incidents take place every week," said Andreas Harsono, who is doing research in Indonesia for Human Rights Watch.
The nuts have been delayed as Papua's resources have attracted an influx of migrants from other parts of Indonesia.
The province's 3.5-milion population is 83% Christian, but demographic figures are changing as Muslim economic migrants from the densely populated Indonesian islands of Java, Sumatra and Sulawesi arrive.
Javan shopkeepers, "varungi," sell fried chicken and a mixture of "gado-gado" vegetables served with peanut sauce.
The locals are trying to withstand the competition.
"Migrants started selling chicken and vegetables cheaper in the traditional market than the indigenous people of Papua," explains abet Yow, a twenty-year-old Paniai native who moved to Jayapura, the province's administrative center, because of her work.
"Because of this, the indigenous people of Papua mom (women) Papua have lost their market."
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, popularly known as Jokowi, vowed to address inequality and rights abuses in Papua during his presidential campaign in 2014.
On his way to the presidential palace in Jakarta, the former carpenter secured the support of 27 of Papua's 29 districts, including Paniai.
But almost nothing has changed in Papua, and locals feel betrayed.
"Our hearts are broken because in 2014 we voted for Jokowi, expecting him to fulfill our hopes for justice," says Yow.
In fact, just two months after the October inauguration, Jokowi Paniai survived the tragedy.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children were on the street singing Christmas anthems at a bonfire in Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers on a motorcycle broke out of the darkness.
Terrified children told them they should turn on the headlights.
According to local pastor javedt Tebay, one of the soldiers was offended by their tone and returned with four soldiers a short time later.
According to the victims and eyewitnesses, the soldiers, who were drunk, chased the children and beat them with rifle butts.
Then one of the soldiers shot at a group of children.
One child, 16-year-old Julius eymo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A couple of hours later, someone set fire to the nearby government building of the Electoral Commission, and the next day the situation worsened.
About 1,000 Papuan men, women and children gathered on a football field in front of a local police station and a military command center to demand justice.
They brought with them ritual hunting bows and performed waitha, a dance of the Papuan Mee Pago tribe: they ran circles and depicted bird singing.
Some protesters began throwing stones at the police station and the military base.
When the situation escalated, the soldiers were given an order by internal radio: "If the crowd resisted more than three times, shoot them," as he said in an official document seen by the correspondents of TIME magazine, but which was not published in the local media.
Fifty-six-year-old Eremias Kayame, head of the Keh Koto district in Enarotali, felt the danger approaching and called for calm, asking the crowd to disperse to their homes.
No one wanted to listen to him.
"When I turned, I was suddenly hit by a bullet in my left wrist," he told TIME magazine, standing on the porch of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayame still doesn't know who fired, but says the bullet came from the shereng side of the assembled soldiers.
"There was a crowd, there were a lot of shots," he adds.
A local resident, Alfius Yowa, was hit three times, as his cousin, who witnessed the shooting, tells us.
"I ran up to him and examined his body to make sure it was him," Johanes, who like many Indonesians uses only one name, told TIME magazine.
"I saw that he was dead... I kissed him."
General Yotje Mende, a senior inspector of Papua Police, told reporters that his officers were merely "protecting" their base because it was under attack.
"We have to defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us," Papua police spokesman Commissioner Pujo sulitiyo said in 2015.
"It's a matter of life and death."
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many more were injured.
News of the killings only reached Jakarta the next day.
Three weeks later, Jokowi delivered a ferocious speech in Jayapur in which he expressed condolences to the families of the victims and vowed to address the issue of historic abuses of power in Papua.
"I want this situation to be resolved immediately so that it never happens again in the future," he said.
In October 2016, security minister Wiranto said he would establish a non-judicial organization to put an end to historic human rights abuses.
But almost immediately there were excuses.
"Most of the violations occurred a long time ago.
Some of them took place in the Nineties or at the beginning of the zero.
The fact is that we certainly want to address these violations, but there are procedures to go through, "he said.
Wiranto then retracted his words, speaking to TIME magazine on June 5 in Jakarta, and said he had no plans to set up an organization to deal with complaints in Papua.
Instead, he said, "everything will be decided through the courts."
Viranto, who was accused by the United Nations of "crimes against humanity" in connection with the deaths of more than 1,000 people during the bloody vote for East Timor's independence in 1999, said 11 cases of human rights violations in Papua had already been resolved, including the Paniai incident.
The families of the victims from Paniai met with such statements with grim distrust.
"I've been questioned four times in the last three years, but there's been absolutely no change," says Johanes.
"I'm tired."
He says that years later he still lives in fear.
"I'm scared," he says.
"I am afraid that I will be arrested by the military, I am afraid that I will be shot."
His brother Jacobus also expressed the opinion that the residents of Paniai are afraid to discuss the incident.
He said he was beaten by the military after helping to bury four victims.
"After we buried the bodies, the military came after me," he says.
The shooting did not stop.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police fired at villagers in the nearby Paniai district of deiyai.
In a clash between villagers and a construction company manager who refused to help take an unconscious man to hospital, one person was killed and 17 others were injured, including children.
A man, 20-year-old Ravianus Dove, who drowned while fishing in a nearby river, died on his way to hospital.
Angry villagers protested in front of the office of a construction site owned by the company.
According to police, the villagers threw stones at the officers, who responded by firing warning shots.
But locals claim that the mobile brigade (Indonesian Special Forces) began shooting at the crowd and killed one person.
"We were in such panic, we are afraid of retaliation," domingu Badia, a twenty-nine-year-old who lives near the hospital and saw the wounded being hastily delivered, told TIME magazine.
"I hid at home for two days."
The deiyai Parliament demanded that the officers involved in the incident be called to account, and that the mobile police brigade be withdrawn from the region.
Paniyai has always been a sick place for the Indonesian government.
The lack of meaningful development is causing resentment among the Meye, Monie, Dani and Damal Tribes scattered throughout the green-covered central highlands of Papua.
Many have joined the Free Papua Movement (OPM), a rebel army that claims to protect the rights of Papuans by launching sporadic attacks and kidnapping raids on Indonesian soldiers.
Some of OPM's top leaders come from Paniai, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel yudas Kogoya.
In response, thousands of people have been arrested in Paniai in recent years and arbitrarily detained by the military under the pretext of "defending national independence."
Some never returned.
Among the population of Papua, Paniai is considered a "sad, forgotten place."
Poverty increases discontent.
A small portion of rice sold in Enarotali is too expensive for locals.
Bread is not available to the same extent.
People here grow everything they eat: Mostly a note, as well as some fruits and leafy vegetables.
Agriculture is the work of women, each of whom can look after four or five fields of sweet potatoes.
They usually retain most of the harvest for the family, and the rest is sold on the local market.
Ten tubers of note cost only 10,000 Indonesian rupees (75 cents).
Over time, there has been an increase in the economic disparity between indigenous Papuans and new migrants, who have arrived in large numbers since the introduction of new flights to Nabire Airport.
Few existing vacancies usually go to better-educated and well-off migrants.
Papuans rarely have enough money or the necessary skills to run their own competitive business.
"Young people don't want to stay in the village... because there's no work or money here," says John gobaei, chairman of the Paniai Tribal Council.
Isolation keeps Papua away from the views of the rest of the world.
Moreover, restrictions on the work of the international media remain tight.
Earlier this year, French journalists Frank escudi and Basil lonshan were deported from Papua for "lack of coordination with the relevant organizations" despite being given rare video permits.
According to Phelim Kine, deputy Asia director at Human Rights Watch, promises made during Jokowi's election campaign to lift restrictions on the media in order to promote transparency and development have not been fulfilled.
"Foreign journalists trying to report from the rebel eastern Indonesian provinces, Papua and West Papua are now facing new dangers: visa denials and blacklisting," he said in a statement.
The lack of press attention means that international pressure on the Indonesian government is largely confined to Papua's immediate neighbours.
In March, six Pacific States - Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands and Solomon Islands - asked the UN Human Rights Council to investigate "various and widespread violations" in Papua, including the Paniai shooting.
The same countries have supported OPM in the past.
A spokesman for Indonesia's Foreign Ministry, arramanata Nasir, brushed off the group's statement, telling reporters in Jakarta that "Indonesia still has a democratic system and a free press, so it would be difficult to hide evidence of human rights violations."
Locals want more foreign governments to pay attention to the situation.
When an official delegation from the Netherlands, led by the Dutch ambassador for human rights, KIIS van Baar, visited Jayapura on May 4, the locals broke their silence, saying: "We want freedom," according to the source, who also attended the meeting, but wished to remain anonymous.
Indonesia will hold a new presidential election in 2019, but Papuans say they are unlikely to vote for Jokowi again.
"Jokowi is a man who has good intentions, but he is surrounded by people involved in the Paniai shooting," says ghobai, chairman of the tribe's Council.
He wants Jokowi to know that the residents of Paniai, apart from living in the shadow of the threat from the scarlet army, are mired in poverty, and their education and health care are in a miserable state.
Ghobai says that the residents of Paniai, like other Papuans, consider their vote, given for Jokowi, a debt that he has to pay.
"They don't need money, they just want justice," he says.
Despite threats and intimidation, the families of the victims of the Paniai shooting carried out the latest symbolic act of defiance: they buried the body of one of the victims on a plot of land directly opposite the police and military station.
Knowing that justice will probably never prevail, they will at least not allow the guilty to forget about their crimes.
"They killed a member of our family," Jacobus says, without raising his head.
"What else could we do?"
