EPA Chief Pruitt drops intention to delay implementation of Obama's emissions-reduction rules
The day after the 15-state lawsuit, the head of the Environmental Protection Agency reversed his decision to delay implementation of Obama's regulations to reduce air pollution and smog.
Pruitt attributed his decision to the fact that his agency now listens more than under previous administrations to the needs of individual state environmental regulators.
He made no mention of a lawsuit against his previous position filed in a federal appeals court.
The dispute revolved around the October 1 deadline for the States to ensure compliance with the 2015 Earth-level ozone standards.
Pruitt announced in June that he would delay their compliance by one year to give his office more time to study the plan and avoid "inconsistency with local decisions or obstacles to economic growth."
Pruitt, who before being appointed by President Trump to his current position was Oklahoma's attorney general, has long been known as a consistent opponent of stricter environmental regulations.
Since moving to Washington, Pruitt has repeatedly blocked or delayed the introduction of regulations opposed by the chemical or gas-oil industry.
The unexpected change of course on Wednesday is another legal defeat of puitt's policy of returning to previous norms.
Last month, a federal appeals court in Washington ruled that the head of the EPA had exceeded his authority in an effort to delay implementation of an Obama administration rule requiring oil and gas companies to track and reduce methane leaks.
In a statement released Wednesday night, Pruitt suggested that by dramatically changing course on ozone standards, he was simply fulfilling the EPA's duty to cooperate with the States in a comprehensive process of timely implementation of the new standards.
"Under previous administrations, the EPA was often unable to meet the deadline, then waited for lawsuits from activist groups and others and discussed deadlines during the settlement of the case," said Pruitt, who filed more than a dozen lawsuits against the EPA in his previous position.
"We don't believe in regulation through trials, and we take the deadlines seriously.
We also take seriously our Charter and the power it gives us. "
However, the EPA said in a statement that Pruitt may at some point again use his "powers to delay and other statutory powers" to make sure that the regulations are "jcyjdfys on a clear course and on all available information."
Republicans in Congress are pushing for a broader overhaul of the rules on ozone.
The bill, approved by the House of Representatives last month, seeks to delay implementation of the 2015 rules by at least eight years.
The Senate has yet to vote on the issue.
New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, who led a coalition of states filing a lawsuit against the EPA this week, said the group intends to continue legal pressure.
"The EPA's course changes - after our lawsuits - are an important victory in the fight for the health and safety of 6.7 million New Yorkers and more than 115 million Americans who are directly affected by smog covering their cities," Schneiderman said.
New York's lawsuit was joined by California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont and Washington, as well as the District of Columbia.
Ozone at ground level occurs when conventional pollutants from machines, power plants, refineries and chemical plants and other sources react in the atmosphere with sunlight.
The resulting smog can cause serious breathing problems in sensitive people, leading to thousands of premature deaths a year.
Health advocates and environmental advocates welcomed Pruitt's unexpected change of course.
"It's sad to think about how much pressure it took to get this perfectly logical step from the person charged with protecting the air we breathe," said Laurie Anne bird of the Center for Biological Diversity.
"We must continue to resist the Trump administration's ideological campaign and protect those who pollute the air and their special interests."
