How football's financial rules will affect Neymar's move to Paris
Rules aimed at preventing unlimited spending by European football clubs will not prevent Neymar's world-record transfer from Spain's Barcelona to France's Paris Saint-Germain.
Whatever the consequences may come further down the chain, for Paris Saint-Germain by UEFA, the governing body that controls European football, in whose power to ban teams from the prestigious Champions League tournament.
It follows from the Financial Fair Play rules introduced by UEFA in 2011 that PSG will eventually have to show that Neymar's transfer was funded without major losses.
Barcelona were paid 222 million euros ($262 million) just to free the Brazilian from his contract, and Neymar will receive a salary that will reach tens of millions of dollars a year.
Here are some of the financial aspects of Neymar's move to France.
PSG can definitely sell out to hire Neymar and add him to the galaxy of other stars, given the team's funding from Qatar's Energy-rich ruling family.
Clubs have the right to spend large sums to acquire players, but they have to balance them at the expense of legitimate sources of income in order to reach the threshold of profitability in their football business.
"FFF" was introduced by Michel Platini after his election as UEFA president in 2007.
The former French footballer believed that clubs that were in huge debt in their quest for success were, in fact, swindling and risking ruin if banks or owners stopped financing.
In 2011, FFF stopped focusing on club debt and instead switched to tracking their losses.
As a result of this change, the business model originally used by Roman Abramovich in Chelsea in 2003 - to buy a club with good potential and then spend heavily to improve the team and create a global brand - has become a difficult plan.
During this three-year valuation period, which captures 2018, clubs can suffer losses of 30 million euros.
And, despite the fact that Platini was disgracefully removed from the presidency in 2015, his successor at UEFA, Alexander cheferin, is still determined to deter excessive spending.
"Of course, the FPF is alive, and we will tighten the rules moving forward," Andrea Traverso, who controls the FPF at UEFA, told the Associated Press last week.
Although PSG will pay for the buyout of Neymar's contract at a time, it can distribute this amount for reporting throughout the duration of his contract.
Neymar has signed a five-year contract, so the transfer value can be shown in the annual report as a cost of 44.4 million euros over the next five years.
During the first wave of FPF sanctions in 2014, heavy sanctions were imposed on PSG, as well as on Abu Dhabi-owned Manchester City.
PSG were fined 60 million euros (at that rate it is 82 million dollars), which was later reduced to 20 million euros, and were ordered to limit the composition of their team in the Champions League during the 2014-10 season to 21 players instead of the usual 25.
UEFA tracks clubs that may try to outdo its financial inspections by inflating their income at the expense of companies associated with the club's owners.
Although the Qatari company could have siphoned off PSG, if the amount of funding was deemed to exceed standard market prices, UEFA would not have allowed it to be considered a legitimate income.
This is exactly what happened in 2014, when UEFA ruled that the amount of funding for PSG from the Qatar Tourism Authority had been inflated.
It was reported that part of Neymar's earnings to PSG could come in the form of payments from the Organizing committee of the 2022 World Cup in Qatar.
But PSG and Qatar 2022 deny that Neymar will become a World Cup ambassador, and a similar manner could easily be detected by UEFA inspectors.
Past sanctions imposed on PSG mean UEFA will be even more careful to monitor any attempts to circumvent the rules.
According to people familiar with the situation on Thursday, UEFA did not have preliminary discussions with PSG about Neymar's transfer.
They communicated with the Associated Press on condition of anonymity, as they are not authorized to discuss the situation of PSG.
According to the latest published report, in 2015-1016 "PSG" received more than 10 million euros in profit on turnover of 542.4 million euros.
The accounts for the last financial year have not yet been published.
PSG expects Neymar's arrival to be favorable ground for sponsorship deals, the sale of paraphernalia and T-shirts with the team's logo.
The club assumes that turnover will increase by at least 30 percent due to the hiring of a new player.
Undoubtedly angry that one of the best players is leaving, the Spanish league tried to prevent Neymar's transfer, saying that "PSG" will violate the financial "fair play."
"This is an obvious case of" financial doping, "with the club and the state," La Liga president Javier Tebas told Spanish newspaper AS, referring to Qatar as the ultimate owner of PSG.
Arsenal coach Arsene Wenger, whose club is owned by the American sports tycoon, shares La Liga's doubts about the club's funding by the state.
"These are all the consequences of equity participation, and it has completely changed the landscape of football over the past fifteen years," Wenger said on Thursday.
"When the club belongs to the country, everything is possible.
It becomes very difficult to observe financial fair play, because the country can have many ways and many reasons to be represented by such a serious player.
The order and places of taking the oath of office will be determined by the President
Where and how new Russian citizens will pledge allegiance to the Russian Federation will be determined by the president - such amendments to the second reading in the relevant law developed by the State Duma Committee on legislation and state construction.
A week ago, the deputies planned to directly determine the procedure for taking the oath of office in the law.
Children under the age of 18, as well as the incapacitated, will be exempt from taking the solemn oath, according to the revised text of amendments to the bill "on Citizenship of the Russian Federation" (there is at the disposal of "Izvestia"), which the committee will consider on July 11 before the second reading at its meeting.
President Vladimir Putin supported the idea of swearing in Russian citizenship instead of formally signing documents on June 6 during a meeting with Speaker of the State Duma Vyacheslav Volodin.
The deputies framed this idea in the form of an amendment to the second reading of the bill, providing for the abolition of the decision to issue citizenship to those who were subsequently convicted of a number of crimes of a terrorist or extremist nature: for example, for public incitement to terrorism or its public justification in the media or on the Internet (part 2 of Article 205.2 of the Criminal Code), as well as for the hijacking of an aircraft, train or water transport, but only if the act is connected with terrorism (part 4 of Article 211 of the Criminal Code).
According to the bill, the logic of it was: by issuing citizenship documents, a person signs up to a promise to comply with Russian law-by taking the path of extremism, he violates that promise.
The bill in April was introduced in the State Duma by leaders of Duma factions Vladimir Vasilyev ("United Russia"), Gennady Zyuganov (Communist Party), Vladimir Zhirinovsky (LDPR), Sergey Mironov ("Fair Russia") and the speaker of DG Vyacheslav Volodin.
On May 19, the deputies accepted it in the first reading.
Last week, the DG Committee on State Construction and legislation approved the text of the bill for the second reading, but now it has been revised again.
Now it says that the order of taking the oath will be established by the President of the Russian Federation.
Earlier, parliamentarians were going to describe the procedure directly in the law "on Citizenship of the Russian Federation," indicating that the ceremony should take place in a solemn setting in front of the state emblem and the flag of Russia in the presence of a representative of the Ministry of Internal Affairs.
However, it was not clear from the text of the bill where such an event should take place - the list of places where it is possible to place the coat of arms of the Russian Federation is regulated by the relevant federal constitutional law.
They include courts, offices of heads of state bodies of subjects, municipalities, judges, prosecutors, heads of federal executive bodies, etc.
Most likely, it could also be a registry office.
To say a solemn oath wishing to obtain citizenship of the Russian Federation will be after officials check their documents.
But the person will receive the Russian passport only after taking the oath of office, according to the revised text.
A week ago, the draft stated that the oath of office should precede the signing of the decree.
The updated text says that Russia will be sworn in from the age of 18, not from the age of 14.
There is still a rule under which those who are incapable or restricted will be exempt from taking the oath, as well as those who cannot pronounce, read or sign the text of the oath.
In addition, the President of the Russian Federation has the right to exempt from this procedure and "other persons,"
The updated bill also sets out a special procedure for admission to Russian citizens of Ukraine, who are considered native speakers of the Russian language.
They will have to formally renounce their Ukrainian citizenship by submitting an application to the authorized body of Ukraine for this purpose.
A certified copy of the application will need to be handed over to Russian officials.
Renunciation of "Alien" citizenship, as it is now, will not be necessary if it is provided for by an international treaty or if it is not possible "for reasons beyond the control of the person."
The corresponding amendment to the law was proposed by a group of deputies, among them the first deputy speaker of DG Ivan Melnikov (Communist Party), Natalia povetskaya, Pavel Krasheninnikov and Ayrat Farrahov (all - "United Russia").
I think many of you know that it is unrealistic to get a certificate from Ukraine, just impossible.
Accordingly, a lot of people are waiting for the decision of their fate on the citizenship of the Russian Federation, - explained the day before the head of the Duma Committee on State Construction and legislation Pavel Krasheninnikov (er).
In addition, the text made it clear that restrictions on certain positions for foreigners would not apply to those who had renounced their "other" citizenship in writing and had surrendered their former passport to the Ministry of Internal Affairs of Russia, but "for reasons beyond his control" he had not ceased to be considered a citizen of another country.
Now foreigners are forbidden to hold positions in the municipal service, to be hired to work for facilities and in organizations whose activities are connected with the security of Russia.
Also, a person with dual citizenship or residence permit of another country cannot become a member of the State Duma or a member of the Federation Council.
It is planned that the law should come into force on September 1, 2017, by which time the necessary by-laws should be ready.
