Judges are offered protection from Presidents
The Presidential Council for Human Rights (HRC), on behalf of Vladimir Putin, has developed proposals to strengthen the independence of the judiciary.
HRC proposes to limit the powers of the presidents of the courts and to introduce their electability.
For the courts of appeal and cassation, HRC wants to introduce special districts that will not be tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The Supreme Court must also submit its proposals within the framework of the presidential mandate.
HRC has finalized proposals that will strengthen the independence of Russian justice.
This work was carried out by HRC on behalf of Vladimir Putin on January 3, 2017, which the president gave after meeting with members of the Council.
At the meeting with the members of the Council on December 8, 2016, some cases of judicial arbitrariness, as well as problems of public control in places of detention of citizens were discussed (see "Kommersant" of December 9).
The outcome of the HRC was 25 proposals that address both the independence of the judiciary and the detection of judicial errors, as well as the financing of the courts and legal education.
One of the ideas of Kremlin human rights defenders is to limit the powers of court presidents to increase the independence of the remaining judges.
If the candidate for the position of judge successfully passed the contest and received the support of the judicial community, the president of the court, according to HRC, should submit it for appointment, without the right to refuse, as the law now allows.
It is also proposed that the president be deprived of the right to allocate cases to judges.
A specially written computer program can do this, experts say.
The HRC also considers that the president is not entitled to "predetermine the results of the qualification certification of the judge, initiate his disciplinary action, make decisions on the establishment of additional material payments."
At the same time, the presidential council considers it necessary to move to "the election of the presidents of the courts by the judges themselves" and "to empower them for a relatively short period of time with mandatory rotation."
Now all the presidents of the courts (from Republican to District) are appointed for six years by the President on the proposal of the Chairman of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation.
In order to protect judges from the pressure of regional administrations, HRC proposes to organize a new appeal and cassation in the courts of general jurisdiction.
Now their structure is tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The HRC says that "it is necessary to ensure the organization of separate courts of appeal and cassation not at the level of regional judicial bodies in the constituent entities of the Russian Federation, but in the judicial districts."
The experts are based on the practice of arbitration courts.
They have "judicial districts," which do not coincide with the administrative division in the Russian Federation, but guarantee greater independence from regional officials, who find it difficult to use "telephone law."
The justices of the peace of the HRC proposes to strengthen the people's judges to deal with certain "categories of civil and administrative cases" with their participation.
For example, deprivation of parental rights, reinstatement, protection of honor and dignity, deprivation of driver's license, etc.
"These are only our proposals," explained "Kommersant" member of the HRC, retired Constitutional Court judge Tamara morshakov.
She also recalled that the president's instruction applied not only to HRC, but also to the Supreme Court (SC), which has yet to disclose its proposals.
There is still time for the armed forces (among the co-perpetrators - the Prosecutor General's Office and the Commissioner for human rights in the Russian Federation) to carry out the order.
To report to Vladimir Putin on how effectively the independence of justice is ensured in the Russian Federation, the chairman of the Armed Forces Vyacheslav Lebedev has until September 1.
Live the high life: half-floor and cunning designer receptions have turned this small apartment into Earls Court into a spacious dwelling
Joan Lee, a former banker keen on real estate repairs, moved from a spacious house in Knightsbridge to an apartment in Earls Court in 2014.
The apartment is on the ground floor of a nice model house in the style of Queen Anne, and in favor of the new design says that Joan did not collect her belongings and did not move again.
"I used to live with my ex in Knightsbridge in a much larger area," Joan says.
"I was looking for something comparable for my money.
I was shown this apartment in Earls Court, and there were the same high ceilings.
I fell in love with her and offered a price on the same day. "
Since the first viewing, the 1,000-square-foot apartment has undergone a complete renovation.
Originally, it was a one-bedroom apartment with a complex layout - to get into the bedroom, you had to go through the kitchen - and Joanna wanted to add storage space and a half-floor to squeeze the most out of the generous height of the ceilings.
"I wanted high ceilings, big windows, a lot of light.
Those were my demands, "she says.
To that end, she hired Erfan Azadi from the Notting Hill architectural and design studio Duck & Shed to use the 12.5-foot-high ceilings and create a home that would not only be a successful project, but fit Joan for life.
The ceiling was not high enough to accommodate two rooms one above the other, so the architectural challenge was to create a half-floor where you could stand at full height.
Erfan had to think creatively to cope with the brif.
"Working with steel structures is very difficult," he explains.
"We needed to place the premises so that they were one over the other, and we didn't have to bend.
It was necessary not just to build a simple platform, but to bend the structures so that they were at the right height and allowed to use the rooms from above and below. "
This decision allowed Erfan to arrange two full-size rooms one over the other in the allotted space - and many more interesting.
From the half floor through the vintage copper light window from "Retrouvius" there is a view of the chic living room below.
Mirrored furniture with gold finish, silver accents and vintage lighting devices from Serge Muya set the style of the project.
The use of mirrors plays a role in adding staginess, space and light.
The short corridor is framed with mirrors to make it seem longer.
In the kitchen, the Mirror protection panel appears to be a window into another room.
At the entrance, mirror cabinets serve to store all Joan's dishes.
To create a sense of a more luxurious space, the beauty of the living room can country the kitchen when it is not used.
There is nothing new in the folding kitchens.
The uniqueness of this kitchen is that it's a moving up door, like in a garage.
"Engineering art was involved here," Erfan says of the steel-reinforced wood-fibre shield door.
"It is equipped with a counterweight, so when you push the door up, it slips very easily."
With a reasonable use of space and storage space, Joan got an extra 16 square metres, an extra bedroom and improved layout.
"At the end of the day, floor area is exactly what you're going to sell, that is, what your real estate is valued at," says Erfan.
"Roughly speaking, the real estate agent will come in and make calculations based on the floor area."
Here they were able to increase the floor area using quality materials that give the space a touch of luxury.
"Materials are something we touch, so they help create an emotional connection with the house," says Erfan.
"No one falls in love with the electrical wiring in the walls.
It is important, but it does not hit the strings of our hearts. "
This is a testament to the fact that, due to good design and a larger scale, the apartment can turn from something ordinary into something amazing.
In fact, like Joan, you can decide to stay.
The government approved the establishment of the Cultural Policy Commission
The Russian government has approved the establishment of a commission on state cultural policy.
The decision was published on the government's website.
According to the document, the main task of the Commission will be to develop and adjust strategic approaches to the implementation of cultural policy.
The Commission will also develop draft strategies for cultural policy, clarify objectives and prepare new programmes for its implementation.
Deputy Prime Minister of the Russian Federation has been appointed head of the Commission.
The composition of the Commission will be approved separately.
Russian Prime Minister Dmitry Medvedev in 2016 approved a plan to implement the strategy of the state cultural policy until 2030.
The plan includes 193 activities and includes measures to expand the influence of Russian culture in other countries, preserve the common cultural space and cultural heritage, and it will help create conditions for the development of culture in the country.
