The brothers are fighting for a real estate empire worth more than $500 million
Two brothers are fighting for one of Victoria's largest empires in real estate trading worth more than $500 million - Forty years after their Italian ancestors founded the dynasty.
Former Carlton Football Club director and property developer Colin de Lutis lives in Turak Palace through three doors from his younger brother Paul, who filed a lawsuit against him in the Supreme Court to share possessions and assets.
Paul has wanted to get out of the family business since 2014, but there is still a bitter dispute in the Supreme Court over the terms of the divorce.
Along with their mother Anna, the brothers own 87 properties worth more than half a billion dollars bought since their family bought a shop on Smith Street in Collingwood in 1973.
There, the family founded the firm "Westco Jeans," which grew into a network of 160 outlets.
It was sold in 1999 for $85 million.
The money has been invested in real estate, and the De Lutis family's list of properties today includes office buildings, development sites in Brunswick and Sorrento, apartments on the Gold Coast and in Mount Buller and shopping malls in the suburbs.
Under an arrangement with his late father, Colin - whom Paul describes as the "main driving force and dominant personality" of the de Lutis family - owns about two-thirds of the company's assets, while Paul owns about one-third.
According to the court, this means that Colin's property is 316 million and Paul's is 176 million.
The division of property and money has become a stumbling block for the floor.
"The section proposed by Colin gives him, in my opinion, the best parts of the property," he wrote in his first testimony in 2015.
Last Friday, after several failed attempts at reconciliation, the first Supreme Court hearings were held.
The brothers are now arguing over who will control the existing business - from which, according to Paul, Colin excluded it.
Colin argues that this is not the case, but accuses Paul of incompetent management of certain objects.
In testimony given by Colin at the start of the trial, he says he hopes to resolve the dispute.
"My Italian roots make me consider the family the highest priority," he wrote.
Court costs are rising as a snowball: hundreds of pages of testimony, emails and reports from companies such as Deloitte, Pitcher Partners and Charter Keck Cramer have been attached to the case; both sides have attracted the most prominent lawyers, including Royal lawyer Allan Myers, and the best shake-ups.
Mrs. de Lutis and her late spouse, Luigi, were immigrants from Italy; since the late 1950s, they have run dairy bars and gastronomes, and in the early 1970s bought a store in Brunswick.
Under financial guarantees, they bought a shop in Collingwood in which Colin opened the first family jeans store.
Colin says he launched Westco when he was "in the last grades of school, and Paul was then a boy (about 10 years old)."
Anna de Lutis says they and Luigi, who died in 2012, hoped to hand over their possessions to their sons without conflict.
"Luigi often told me that he did not want the brothers to be dealt with in court," she wrote.
Two other brothers, Mark and Luke, are no longer in the de Lutis group of companies; Colin says Mark got 10 million when he went out of business, and Luke 26 million.
According to Paul, both Luke and Mark were "unhappy with the financial conditions of their secession."
Colin was not a public figure, although he was a former member of the AFL club's board of directors and, according to a 2015 biography of Eddie McGuire, TV's best friend.
Fairfax Media contacted Colin and Paul and their lawyers on Friday.
Only Colin replied, with a text message saying that since the case had not yet been heard in court, "I have nothing to say about the truth."
"I am very, very sorry that my brother Paul decided to file a lawsuit against me and tremble in court the name of our family," he wrote.
In mid-2016, Colin wrote in testimony that he had tried to satisfy his brother's demands.
"Our father would not like to see Paul and I argue in court," he said, adding that he "still hopes for a resolution of the conflict."
On Friday, that hope apparently dissipated.
"The judgment in our case will soon be rendered by the court," Colin wrote.
Trump's new chief of staff plans to limit the flow of information to the president.
Others tried to do so and were defeated.
Maybe John F. Kelly will actually succeed.
In that case, he will be the first.
Politico reports that the new White House chief of staff plans to limit the flow of information coming to President Trump, including news reports from the media - hoping to keep the boss in a calmer state.
That's what reporter Josh Dosie reports.
"At a meeting held by the new White House chief of staff, John F. Kelly, with the leadership of the staff on his first working day, he outlined a major problem in the White House under President Donald Trump that he hopes to address: poor channels of information coming to the president."
Kelly told staff that the information should go through him-in paper form or through briefings - because the president would be better off making decisions if he got the right information.
Kelly's diagnosis is perfectly correct, but others have already failed in trying to pacify Trump by tracking the flow of information to him.
President Trump's relationship with television developed decades ago-and now that he's in the White House, his habit of watching TV is still strong.
"When Trump, as a candidate, resented the unfair coverage of the campaign, it was helpful to demonstrate to him that he was getting fair coverage in publications that could be repersuaded," Sam Nanberg, a former adviser to the electoral staff, told Politico in February.
Tara Palmeri wrote in Politico at the time that "according to six former members of the electoral staff, in order to keep Trump's Twitter habit under control, it was necessary to ensure that there was a constant stream of praise in the information coming to him personally."
It's a good thing.
But the idea that Trump's Twitter habit was ever "under control" is simply ridiculous.
Maybe these members of the electoral staff know something we don't know - for example, that, if it weren't for them, Trump's tweets would be even more provocative.
We may never know about the tweets that Trump has not published.
If his staff kept him out of trouble at least a few times, their efforts were not in vain.
But no one has always been able to keep Trump from pouring oil into the fire.
Part of the problem is that in a White House divided into rival factions, people are constantly trying to advance their agenda by giving Trump material - reliable or not-that confirms their views.
"Politico" - just to this story - wrote in May about the tendency of advisers to constantly tweak the president with dubious information.
Here is one example described by reporter Shane Goldmacher:
"Current and former Trump staffers say Trump can react very sharply to negative press reports, especially those containing dangerous leaks of information, and won't rest until he finds who was behind them.
This happened in late February, when someone subpoenaed the president with a printout of an article with GotNews.com, the website of Internet provocateur Charles K. Johnson, in which deputy chief of staff Katie Welsh was accused of being "behind a number of leaks" at the White House.
Never mind that Johnson is forever bandied about on Twitter for aggressive behavior, that he did not present specific facts or that in the past he launched false accusations and then refused them.
Trump read the article and proceeded to question the staff about Welsh. "
Goldmacher adds that then-chief of staff Reince Priebus and Secretary of staff Rob Porter "tried to build a system to manage the flow of papers that Trump receives and document them."
How did it work?
Three months later, Kelly is trying to do the same.
Maybe he will prove to be a more effective manager than Priebus, but Trump still has an impulsive nature, and his aides are still fighting each other for influence.
These constant factors make Kelly's task very difficult.
Tyumen Prosecutor's Office fights HIV-dissident
The Prosecutor's Office challenged the ruling of the Kalininsky District Court of Tyumen, which dismissed the criminal case against a local woman who had a young daughter died of HIV.
According to the investigation, the child died because the mother was an HIV dissident and refused treatment.
However, the court relieved her of her responsibility in connection with her reconciliation with the injured father.
The prosecutor's office believes that the crime cannot go unpunished so as not to set a precedent for other HIV dissidents.
The case against the resident of Tyumen was initiated under part 1 of Article 109 of the Criminal Code (causing death by negligence) in April - after her three-year-old daughter died from HIV infection in stage 4.
According to the prosecutor's office, the mother herself is HIV-positive.
"The woman did not treat herself and refused to treat her daughter, believing that HIV infection does not exist," the prosecutor's office of Tyumen region explained.
The criminal case came to the Kalininsky District Court of Tyumen, which on July 25 decided to terminate it.
The petition was filed by the father of the dead girl, explaining that he "forgave his wife, has no claims against her, she repaired the harm and apologized."
The Prosecutor's Office disagreed with the Court's decision and appealed, demanding that the decision to dismiss the case be overturned and sent to a new hearing.
The girl died, and it is impossible to repair the harm caused by the crime.
The HIV-infected mother, contrary to the recommendations of doctors, refused to examine the baby and treat her from a dangerous infection, "the press service of the prosecutor's office reported.
According to the oversight body, she should be punished, otherwise other HIV dissidents will follow her example.
As told in the Tyumen AIDS Center, now in the Tyumen region about 12 children with HIV do not receive medical care because of the refusal of parents.
"And this situation has already improved - during the year of the work of the special group, half of parents who categorically refused to treat children for HIV, changed their opinion - allowed to carry out diagnostics, began to take drugs," - said the spokeswoman of the AIDS Center Elena Loseva.
According to her, it is impossible to influence parents by legislative means, and as a result not all HIV-infected children can be found - mothers do not allow them to examine, hide, run away with children from hospitals.
The dangers posed by HIV dissidents
At the end of last year, St. Petersburg social scientists presented the results of Russia's first study of the so-called HIV dissident movement.
HIV dissidents are referred to as people who deny the existence of HIV and refuse to take medication.
Doctors and activists of AIDS-service NGOs call such views anti-Medical, and in their dissemination see a serious threat.
The grisly photo shoot, which ended in tragedy, took place on Thursday, August 3, at grečany railway station in Khmelnitsky.
