Roma overcame the moat and returned to "millionaires Street"
Some of the West Midlands' most wealthy homeowners are once again at odds with the determined Roma, who overcame the moat dug out by municipal authorities to retake the field next to their homes.
Gypsies parked 20 houses on wheels in a field bordering the wealthy Solihull Street, dubbed "millionaires Street."
Bringing with them horses, babies and many houses on wheels, they returned after being driven out no further than in May, and they were not prevented by the moat dug by the municipal authorities to prevent their incursions.
This tactical company found a gap in the defensive structures and pushed its vehicles through a section that was left unfenced to leave room for the path.
Angry residents attacked the municipality of Solihull, saying it had proved "incapable of solving this problem."
An anonymous local resident said: "They came here on Monday evening, after they were driven from Bentley Heath, where they shoved stones at passers-by."
The municipality should be shamed and forced to act because they are totally incapable of solving this problem.
The Gypsies were here in May, they were driven away, and here they returned again.
Last night, even more gypsies arrived, and today, perhaps even more.
"The municipality of Birmingham knows how to solve this problem, they get long-term court orders to protect their parks," she added.
I live on Streetsbrook Road, and I don't like that I continue to pay council tax, and the municipality can't even put an end to it. "
One resident, who wished to remain anonymous, said: "It is ridiculous, we have just seen these Gypsies leave the previous time, and here, please, this attack continues."
This time there were more of them, and we even saw a horse grazing in the meadow. "
A spokesman for Solihull municipality said: "We are aware of the illegal camp on the ground near Streetsbrook Road and are cooperating with Solihull Police; we are taking the necessary legal action to drive them away as soon as possible."
In order to help us collect evidence, it is very important that as many local residents as possible report any anti-social or criminal behaviour to the police on 101.
This makes it possible to get an idea of the situation that the court will consider when we present our case to them.
Crimea corporates Champagne wine factory "new light"
Gup of the Republic of Crimea "Champagne wine factory" new light "" decided to corporatise, having transformed into JSC "Champagne wine factory" new light, "" according to the order of the Minister of Property and Land Relations of Crimea Anna anyukhin.
100% of the company's shares will remain in state ownership of Crimea.
The authorized capital of the joint-stock company will amount to 595.5 million rubles and will consist of 5.955 million ordinary shares with a nominal value of 100 rubles each.
The Ministry of Agriculture of Crimea stated that if within the next three years there are no funds for the modernization of the enterprise, there will be a threat to stop the plant.
The wear and tear of fixed assets in the enterprise is about 60-70%.
For the modernization of the enterprise it is necessary 1.2 billion rubles due to the peculiarities of the organizational and legal form it is obliged to give 50% of the profit to the Budget income.
What remains is not enough to implement the modernization plan.
"Getting money from the owner is problematic, it is difficult to talk about attracting borrowed funds of large credit institutions," deputy head of the Ministry of Agriculture of Crimea Sergey Petelin said in April this year.
The Parliament of Crimea included the enterprise in the forecast privatization plan for 2017.
It was suggested that it should be corporatised and put up for tender.
The source of "Interfax" in the authorities of Crimea estimated the possible value of the sale of the enterprise at $40 million, the investor's investment in modernization - another $30 million.
