Italy is tightening its tone towards NGO ships rescuing migrants.
Italy has warned NGOs that own rescue vessels in the Mediterranean that they will not be able to continue to operate unless they comply with the new rules governing their operations.
"If NGOs do not comply with the new code of conduct, it is difficult to say whether they will be able to continue their activities," Interior Minister Mario minthread said in an interview with the Turin daily newspaper Stampa.
Minthread's warning came a day after Italian authorities confiscated a ship belonging to the German humanitarian organization Jugend Rettet on suspicion that its crew was actually cooperating with traffickers and facilitating illegal immigration.
The humanitarian organization, which has worked for only a year, declined to comment on the merits of the detailed charges brought against it by Italian prosecutor ambrojo Cartosio.
"For us, saving human life is and will remain the highest priority, so we very much regret that we cannot continue to operate in the search and rescue zone now," the organization said in a statement on social networks.
"We will be able to assess all the allegations made now only after we have gathered all the information and are able to assess the situation."
The Italian authorities have been monitoring the vessel "Yuventa," owned by "Jugend Rettet," since October.
His crew is suspected of taking on board migrants who were sent directly by traffickers and allowing smugglers to leave with boats they could re-use.
At least one such meeting is believed to have taken place just 1.3 miles from the Libyan coast, according to the prosecution, the contents of which were published in the Italian media.
The crew is suspected of violating the orders of the Italian coastal authorities, who control rescue operations in the zone, out of humanitarian zeal rather than for any other reason.
The code of conduct assumes mainly that Juventa-type vessels will have an Italian police officer on board to monitor their activities.
So far, only three of the nine NGOs involved in search and rescue operations have agreed to obey the code: Save the Children, Malta's MOAS and Pro-Activa Open Arms from Spain.
The latter said on Thursday that it considered the new rules unnecessary but acceptable provided they did not cause any "meaningful changes or interference" to its rescue operations.
Among those who refused to sign is the Nobel Prize-winning organization Doctors Without Borders (MSF).
Meanwhile, minthread said a sharp decline in recent weeks in the number of migrants arriving in Italy as a result of rescue operations indicated that efforts to support the Libyan Coast Guard and co-operate with local mayors were bearing fruit.
"In recent days we have started to see the light at the end of the tunnel," the minister said.
He announced plans for further talks with Libyan mayors on economic development initiatives and with Chad, the Niger and Mali on measures to reduce the number of migrants leaving those countries in the hope of reaching Europe.
"In Libya, we do not want to be associated with either side of the conflict"
The authorities of the Russian Federation have recently significantly intensified their policy on the Libyan direction, and with visits to Moscow delegations of the opposing Libyan sides have been involved.
The head of the Russian contact group on the intra-Libyan settlement under the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Russian Federation and the State Duma, assistant to the head of the Chechen Republic Lev money told Kommersant what goals Moscow pursues in this region and on whom it relies.
Almost nothing is known about the contact group on Libya that you lead.
Here, say, the contact group on Ukraine - everyone knows about it.
And here is the veil of secrecy.
What exactly are you doing, what are your goals?
The contact group was established at the initiative of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Russian Federation and the State Duma.
Its activities are supervised by Deputy Foreign Minister Mikhail Bogdanov and Adam Delimkhanov (deputy of the Duma from Chechnya).
The latter is authorized to work in the Libyan direction by the speaker of the State Duma Vyacheslav Volodin.
The reason for the formation of the group was the detention in Libya of the Russian tanker "mechanic Chebotarev" (in September 2015, there were 11 people on board. - "Kommersant").
We thought about how to help the crew.
Then a contact group of military specialists, representatives of the State Duma was created, our work was supported by the head of Chechnya Ramzan Kadyrov.
And how did it turn out that it was you who led it?
Since I have been working on Libya since 2008, I have been asked to lead the group.
Our activities were not limited to the release of sailors from the "mechanics of Chebotarev."
We have been able to establish contacts with representatives of all the major factions opposing each other in the Libyan conflict - both from Tripoli (where the UN-recognized government, led by Faiz Saraj, is based) and Tobruk (the seat of Parliament, which opposes the government and supports Marshal Khalifa Haftar, who controls eastern Libya).
Thanks to the active participation of Ahmed Metiga (Deputy Prime Minister of Libya - "Kommersant"), we managed to quickly negotiate the release of Russian sailors.
Then it was decided to make better use of these contacts, to create a contact group.
Its task is to analyze the situation, identify key factors and players, and engage in dialogue with all parties to the conflict.
I would like to emphasize that in Libya we do not want to be associated with any of the parties to the conflict, we have a dialogue with everyone.
How many people are in the contact group and how many of them are permanently in Libya?
The contact group now has five members.
Among them are people with experience in the security forces, including the Ministry of Defense.
We also want to join the team of specialists on the region, representatives of the Institute of the middle east of the Russian Academy of Sciences.
No one is permanently in Libya from our staff, there is no need for it yet.
Are there any Russian military advisers, instructors in Libya now.
And if so, on whose side?
There are no Russian military specialists in Libya.
All the talk and publication about this is not true.
But your contact group includes the former military...
Yes, and their presence is necessary.
For example, when we visit hot spots.
Or cities closed to a certain point for us, such as Misurata (where the militias, which played a role in the overthrow of Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi in 2011 and increased markedly in the following years, are based).
We came to Misurata in January of this year.
We were frightened, they said that there were all Islamists, terrorists.
But it was important for us to assess the situation there, to analyze the real military potential, who is responsible for what, why there are such rumors, what is the real role of Islamists there.
In Misurata, we met with all the representatives of the units that were engaged in the destruction of Isis in Sirte (in December 2016, this city on the Mediterranean coast was recaptured from the militants of the banned Islamic State in Russia - Kommersant).
We wanted to look at them, to get to know these people, to check the information that they were the ones who played a crucial role in the destruction of ISIS in Libya, not Khalifa Haftar, who attributed these services to himself.
And what conclusion have you reached?
The Islamic State in Libya won not Haftar?
It wasn't him who was doing it.
Haftar conducted operations on another front, in Benghazi.
And Isis in Sirte was fought by structures subordinate to the government in Tripoli.
And, by the way, we invited the people who carried out this anti-terrorist operation to Russia.
And they arrived - the visit lasted from 19 to 23 April this year, the Libyan delegation received in the Federation Council, in the Duma, the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Federal Guard.
You, as we have understood, are in all Libyan regions and probably imagine the sentiments of local elites and warlords.
Do you think it will be possible to implement the ceasefire agreements, the elections reached in late July in Paris by Khalifa Haftar and Faiz Saraj?
Or again, as has happened repeatedly in the past, the agreements will be broken, the fighting will resume, the parties will try to seize power alone?
For us a good signal was already the fact that Saraj and Haftar agreed to another meeting, not so long ago it was impossible.
In the recent past, the two leaders have been extremely negative about each other.
And as for Russia's position...
It is often written and said that Moscow actively supports Haftar, many believe in it.
We faced this situation when we were in Misurata, and Haftar was on board the Russian aircraft carrier Admiral Kuznetsov on that day.
It was a coincidence.
But in Misurata, they didn't believe in coincidence.
We were told, "You are probably very brave people, that you came to us today."
But our task is just to show: we do not support Haftar alone, we are engaged in dialogue with all the key actors in the conflict in Libya.
You and Haftar communicated.
Does mutual understanding with Russian partners at the human, emotional level facilitate the fact that he studied twice in the USSR?
And, by the way, does Haftar know Russian?
If he knows Russian, he is very relative.
But the fact that he studied with us, of course, facilitates dialogue with him.
And by the way not only with him.
When we communicate with the military in Tripoli and Misurata, we meet generals who studied either in Russia or back in the Soviet Union.
And here they speak fine Russian.
And they are drawn to Russia, to some extent they feel nostalgic for it.
Do we think that an early lifting of the arms embargo imposed on Libya is likely?
Are your Libyan interlocutors interested in the supply of Russian weapons?
We are interested, of course, but as I said, we do not take sides in this conflict and would not want to arm some to the detriment of others.
We would like everyone to be in roughly equal positions.
With regard to the arms embargo, there are constant calls from Libyans for Russia to help lift it.
The process of drafting a constitution is now well under way in Libya.
We hope that the parties will reach compromise solutions and achieve internal consensus.
Then there should be an election, which was also mentioned at the Saraj and Haftar meeting.
If elections take place and legitimate power is finally elected (and now neither side has such status), it is possible to raise the issue of lifting the arms embargo in the UN Security Council.
Raising this issue now is pointless and dangerous, it will only lead to an escalation of the conflict.
The other day, the media reported that Italy, faced with the problem of African refugees sailing from Libya, feels abandoned by EU allies.
Can Moscow, in this situation, help Italian partners by using its ties with the Libyans?
How realistic, for example, is the option that Haftar's units will establish control of the coast and put an end to the business of smugglers smuggling immigrants to Europe?
A very timely question.
We are actively working on it.
The Italians need Russia's support because Moscow is engaged in dialogue at the same time with Haftar, Saraj, Misurata and the south of the country.
And on this issue, tribes in southern Libya play a big role, and they are ready to cooperate with Russia.
Is it a question of Southerners stopping the flow of migrants on long-distance approaches?
That is, to put it mildly, the buses in which Nigerian migrants go back?
We are trying to achieve that.
But it's not easy.
Some clans and groups have a vested interest in keeping these flows going.
We hope to help unite Southerners in the negotiation process between Saraj, Haftar and tribes in the south.
But for a start, we would like to see a unity of opinion on this issue between Haftar and Saraj.
The head of the government in Tripoli, Faiz Saraj, is considered an Islamist, a supporter of the introduction of sharia law in the country.
To what extent does he hold radical views?
Wouldn't that be an obstacle in building relations with Russia or the West?
I will give my personal opinion of him.
In my opinion, he is, on the contrary, an opponent of radical Islam.
But the Islamists are in his coalition.
Yes, but he himself holds the position that Libya should be an absolutely normal country - moderately Islamic, open to the world.
And he is also actively fighting terrorists.
Where, then, does he have such a reputation?
It is created by those countries that have no interest in Russia communicating with Tripoli.
Tripoli is, after all, the capital, where the legislative, executive and judicial branches are located.
There's the National Petroleum Corporation, the national bank and other government entities.
Of course, some countries were interested in us not going there.
And we mixed all the cards with them and began to actively communicate with both Tripoli and Tobruk.
And we are already reaping the benefits of this work: Rosneft has concluded a cooperation agreement with Libya's state oil company, the NOC.
The director of the NOC, Mustafa Sanalla, with whom the head of Rosneft, Igor Sechin, made a deal, himself directly from Tripoli.
And two weeks ago there was the first shipment of Libyan oil to Rosneft.
What will Russia do with it?
I believe that to resell.
And what are Russia's economic interests in Libya?
There are plans to re-sign the contracts concluded under Muammar Gaddafi.
These include previous arrangements in the transport sector (railway construction), energy (electrification) and a number of others.
And the Libyans have something to pay?
Well, they have oil.
That is to say, as in the case of Iran, is the oil-for-services scheme?
I don't know what the scheme will be, I don't deal directly with these issues.
In fact, the economy is for Russia in Libya and not the main thing.
We are, in fact, engaged in peacekeeping work there.
For us, the main thing is to stop the bloodshed, to help the Libyans agree among themselves so that they can establish order and Libya will cease to be an enabling environment for the development of terrorism.
For Russia, this is the main task - to help the Libyan people and squeeze the terrorists out of there.
Do you have data on the presence in Libya (now or earlier) of radical fighters from Russia or other countries of the former USSR?
One of the tasks of our contact group was to clarify this.
I met with a representative of the Libyan state Security committee, who said that to date, not a single person from Russia and other countries of the former USSR is there.
He said he had about 50,000 telephone records of representatives of Islamist and radical groups (in Libya) and did not speak Russian there.
And from which states are these fighters then?
I would not want to go into these details.
Then let's formulate the question differently.
How many of the Islamist fighters in Libya are Libyans themselves?
There are virtually no Libyans among them, no more than 5% of them.
The rest are strangers.
Can Moscow hold intra-Libyan talks following the example of Paris?
There are such plans.
We are actively negotiating with the Libyans, several delegations from Libya have already visited Moscow, and have declared their readiness to come to Moscow or Grozny.
And when can such negotiations take place?
Now it is hard to say.
Several visits have yet to take place, and then, I hope, there will be clarity about the time and place of the negotiations.
