Michelle Carter's conviction for reports that prompted Conrad Roy's suicide
A Massachusetts woman was sentenced to two-and-a-half years in prison for encouraging her boyfriend Conrad Roy to commit suicide through text messages and phone calls.
Michelle Carter, now 20, will have to serve 15 months of her sentence behind bars and another 5 years of probation.
Carter was found guilty in June of the manslaughter of Conrad Roy, who committed suicide on July 13, 2014.
Roy's father told the hearing on Thursday: "My family has been killed by grief.
My son was my best friend. "
Carter was allowed to remain free pending appeal.
She faced a maximum sentence of 20 years, but her lawyers said both she and Roy suffered from mental disorders.
Carter, dressed in red trousers and a cream blouse, listened to the verdict standing, holding her hands down and lowering her eyes.
"By her actions, she killed Conrad Roy," the prosecutor told the court.
"She interrupted his life to improve her own.
She did not acknowledge responsibility, "she said.
"She has shown no remorse."
But Carter's lawyer said it was a "tragic case that she deeply regrets."
However, Judge Lawrence Monis said he believed her "age, maturity level or even mental illness did not affect her actions in a noticeable way."
The prosecutor read statements from Roy's mother, Lynn Roy, saying: "Not a single day has passed when I would not mourn the loss of my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of me and how I cope - I try to support his sisters despite all the pain that will remain with us forever, "it says.
Roy's sister, Kamdin Roy, said she was haunted by the idea that she would never be able to attend his wedding or become his children's aunt.
"To lose a person who has always been with me since my birth is a pain that will stay with me for the rest of my life," she said.
The case is likely to set a legal precedent because Massachusetts does not have a law that provides for the responsibility of advising a person to commit suicide.
In 2014, when Roy was found dead in a car with symptoms of carbon monoxide poisoning, Carter was 17.
The case caught the attention of the entire country when it was reported that he had been prompted to commit suicide by Carter's message.
"You can hang yourself, jump from the roof, stab yourself don't know there are many ways," she wrote in several messages sent two weeks before his death as he rested with his family.
Moments before her suicide, she wrote, "you have to do this, Conrad" and "You only have to turn on the ignition, and you will become free and happy."
Judge Monis said Carter wanted to get attention through Roy's death, and banned her from communicating with the press to prevent her from getting what she wanted.
The opinions of the lawyers on this matter are divided.
One of the few who defended Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted in 2007 of murdering her British apartment neighbor in Italy and acquitted two years later.
Knox, 30, published her dissenting opinion in the Los Angeles Times, which claimed: "Michelle Carter deserves sympathy and help, not prison."
