"Audi" to modify up to 850,000 diesel cars
A day before the announcement by Audi, BMW said it would offer to upgrade the software in more than 350,000 vehicles.
The chairman of BMW said the company believes "there are more intelligent ways than driving restrictions," referring to European cities - including Munich, where BMW is located - that have considered banning or restricting the use of diesel cars.
Daimler said on Thursday it was modifying three million Mercedes cars in Europe to reduce their diesel exhaust.
None of the companies called their move a recall.
European automakers have actively promoted the use of diesel cars in Europe and the United States to promote compliance with regulations on carbon dioxide emissions.
But nitrogen oxides, which emit diesel engines, are considered carcinogens and can cause asthma.
The cost to automakers of installing equipment that neutralizes the exhaust gases of diesel cars is also rising, and it is becoming difficult to maintain a competitive price for cars.
With German automakers under scrutiny, Chancellor Angela Merkel's government has also been accused of pandering to powerful automakers and ignoring signs of a problem.
Companies try not to repeat the mistakes of Volkswagen, which concealed the use of so-called "defeat devices," which during testing could tweak the amount of harmful gases emitted to comply with the rules, and in the conditions of normal driving shut down.
Several Volkswagen executives have been convicted in the United States, while the rest are under investigation on both sides of the Atlantic.
Last month, a former head of thermodynamics as part of the Audi engine development group was arrested in Germany.
The former manager, zakkeo Giovanni Pamio, an Italian, is therefore not protected from extradition and could face trial in the United States.
Earlier this year, Audi came under a German criminal investigation involving Volkswagen after authorities accused Audi of installing a system to circumvent European ejection rules and expanded an investigation that had previously focused on the United States.
The inclusion of "audi" in the investigation could create serious problems for Volkswagen: the manufacturer of luxury cars is the source of a disproportionate share of Volkswagen's income.
In Astrakhan, a visitor to the cafe paid with fake money
The police received a report from the employee of the branch of the bank about the discovery of a suspicious bill with a value of 5 thousand rubles when the money received from the point of catering was converted.
A study conducted at the Forensic Centre found that it was false.
According to the Ministry of Internal Affairs of Russia in Astrakhan region, the note was paid by one of the visitors of the cafe, who bought shaurma.
It is worth noting that the box office was not equipped with a device to determine the authenticity of bills.
Currently, police officers are installing persons involved in the manufacture and sale of a known fake ticket of the Central Bank of the Russian Federation.
Such crimes are punishable by imprisonment for up to 8 years with a fine of up to 1 million rubles.
