Start-ups that will help your company not become another "Uber"
Aimee Errett wanted to assess the level of satisfaction among her startup's E-commerce staff, but the surveys didn't work.
The answers were often vague, unhelpful or, worse, insincere.
And even though she promised anonymity, some employees did not trust the process.
"He's never been consistent and objective," said Errett, who manages the 75-person San Francisco-based Madison Reed, a hair care e-commerce company.
That's why she turned to third parties for help.
Now there is a new kind of HR start-ups that help companies figure out how their employees feel.
By developing and licensing software whose purpose is to measure employee engagement, they allow companies to do express surveys, contact certain teams and demographic groups, offer employees anonymity and hotline for complaints, and in some cases allow informants to pass top management and contact the Directorate directly.
"Now we have tools like Strava and Fitbit for health monitoring, and where is Fitbit for your company?" says Jim Barnett, co-founder and president of the Redwood City Startup Glint, whose analytical programs are used by companies to measure employee engagement.
Errett said she has reached a greater understanding of what her employees think and feel during her three years of using "Glint."
In addition to express surveys and questionnaires of certain teams, the product offers a heat card of the company and shows in a visual form which divisions have more complaints and which managers have a low approval rating, which allows it to figure out why.
Companies realize little by little that they need to control the workplace, otherwise they will become another "Uber" who was involved in the scandal when a former employee published a blog post describing an aggressive environment in which those who expressed discontent were punished.
For start-ups like "Glint," this desire to control the situation is an opportunity for profitable business.
The "Let's talk about pay" Internet portal, dedicated to financial technology, estimates that the global governance, regulation and compliance industry could cost more than $118.7 billion by 2020.
The Denver, Colorado-based start-up Convercent, which helps companies prevent and detect bad behavior, noted a slight increase in interest and activity earlier this year amid a drop in Uber's reputation.
Convercent has nearly 600 customers, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Recently, "Uber" appeared among the clients.
Like "Glint," "Convercent" allows companies to send tailor-made staff opinion surveys, collect confidential responses in real time and view heat maps of problem areas.
It also provides a hotline for anonymous text messages that allows employees to report bad behavior.
And if the top manager is affected, the complaints go straight to the Directorate.
"The court of public opinion has seized power from the inspectors," said Patrick Quinlan, founder and president of Convercent.
If it turns out that the company is not treating employees well or behaving unethically, even if the inspectors do not intervene, the company could face costly consequences in the form of boycotts by customers, employee outflows and lawsuits, Quinlan said.
Ruby Tuesday, a chain of restaurants with more than 25,000 employees in 500 establishments, has used Convercent for more than a year to make sure employees are aware of the rules and procedures, and offer an easy way to contact the company's head office.
Previously, if a staff member wanted to report a problem, he or she had to search for a telephone number or head office mail, file a formal complaint and hope that it would be taken seriously.
It was often a frightening and embarrassing experience, said James Vitrano, head of the legal department at Ruby Tuesday, who said there was no normal way to track employee complaints.
Now that the company is using the Convercent service, problems that used to be hidden from managers sitting in offices in other cities or states - such as discrimination, haraschange and unfair pay-can be detected and dealt with more quickly.
"I can get closer to a holistic, comprehensive understanding of the situation of employees," said Vitrano, who runs the Ruby Tuesday network's risk management group.
"And we protect our shareholders from litigation with employees."
According to Quinland, companies began to take the ethics, values and involvement of employees more seriously in 2002, after the accounting firm Arthur Andersen collapsed due to ethical violations as a result of the "Enron case."
But it was only when "social networks became widespread" that companies realised that they would not be able to keep their dirty underwear from spreading viral online.
"Before we start using technology to control ethics, people used hope as a strategy," he said.
Both "Glint" and "Convercent" offer their software as a service, charging companies regularly for the use of their products.
This is a business model and an opportunity that has received the approval of venture capital investors who have supported both start-ups.
In February, Convercent received $10 million in funding from firms such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, bringing the company's total capital to $47 million.
Glint received $10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners, bringing the company's total capital to $60 million.
These investments are hardly surprising given the interconnected nature of companies, culture, and venture capital.
A growing body of research demonstrates that today's employees expect more from their jobs than they did before.
In markets with tough competition, such as Silicon Valley, high wages and interesting projects are just the necessary minimum.
Employees want to feel that they are accepted and valued, and that they devote their time to a company with a positive mission.
"When people are happy to work for a company, feel that they are being heard, and that the work they do brings results, they try harder to make such a company successful," said Nina McQueen, vice president of global benefits and employee satisfaction at LinkedIn, where both Convercent and Glint are used.
Investors earn income when companies from their portfolio do well; companies do well when employees are dedicated and involved.
If the analytical tools of a third party promise to increase the dedication and involvement of employees, it is not surprising that they find support.
According to workplace culture experts, it is important to have data on employee engagement.
But the data is useless until the company's Trustees take action.
In fact, if a company asks employees for feedback, it can give the impression that change is coming.
And if change doesn't come quickly enough, or doesn't come at all, frustration can develop, and employees will lose interest.
"If you're going to ask for 4,000 offers, you have to be willing to have 4,000 conversations," says Russell Rath, president of consulting at management firm Kotter International, who has had to see companies make a mistake by relying too much on data collection.
"Because if you don't go to the end, the staff will guess," Did you hear me right?
Don't you care?
And if you don't care, why shouldn't I care? "
According to Errett, Madison Reed, which now conducts monthly employee surveys, is in a position to take action on the same day that anyone reports the problem using "Glint."
And, after collecting feedback from employees unhappy with the speed of decision-making and the quality of communication, she was able to reorganize several teams within the company and introduce communication training to solve problems.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining new knowledge about its employees and hopes that in the long run, this knowledge will help it more effectively retain employees in an industry known for high staff turnover.
"If you don't try to create a culture of transparency, you will lose people," Vitrano said.
If you lose people, you lose customers.
And if you lose customers, you lose companies.
