The beginning of the conflict within the ADB began during the discussion in the Federation Council, when the interregional Banking Council considered new bills, in particular, involving a new classification of banks depending on the size of the authorized capital.
Then Garegin Tosunyan, the president of the ADB, said that according to the association, this bill is passed in the interests of the largest banks, which thus try to limit the opportunities of small and medium-sized banks in the regions, intercepting their clientele.
Among other claims, there was criticism of the central bank, which, according to Tosunyan, is not always justified in withdrawing licenses from some banks, which, however, was objected to by the representative of the Central Bank: many heads of the fined banks, in particular, Vnesheconombank, were part of the governing bodies of the ADB.
Apparently, this exchange of mutually exclusive opinions in a highly sensitive relationship with the main regulator of the banking environment and became a visible reason that fifteen major banks, having declared disagreement with the policy of the ADB, began to prepare for joining the association "Russia," noting that "the effectiveness of the work of the ADB is low, and constructive dialogue within the banking community is not actually held."
Depositors will be better off
How will the matter end?
On the contrary, the reliability of the banking system will increase.
Anatoly Aksakov, who is known for his sensitivity in everything concerning the interests of banks and their clients, is head of "Russia," a high-level professional who is highly valued in the Central Bank: almost all central bank management is present at the annual events of the Association, and all significant legislative initiatives of the regulator pass through expert assessments of "regionals."
In terms of personnel and organization, it is clear that there are no particular shocks.
There is no doubt that ARB finds itself in a difficult financial and managerial situation after losing such powerful and influential participants with their contributions and lobbying opportunities.
However, in this oldest organization, established in 1991, which advocates for the interests of the banking community, there is considerable potential to continue to improve banking legislation and monetary circulation in general.
It is impossible to say that in the association "Russia" with open arms are ready to accept on any terms new members, judging by the reaction of its leader, Anatoly Aksakov ("Maybe too much will want"), who as early as July 21 at a briefing in the press center of the parliamentary newspaper, said that "just the next day representatives of the banks leaving the ADB asked me to consider the possibility to increase the potential of our association" Russia. "
Their proposals are to strengthen the voice of bankers on the association's board, as well as pay more attention to new banking technologies.
Now the negotiation process is underway, the proposals of both sides are being studied, the agenda of the extraordinary congress of the Association, which will be held in Sochi in mid-September within the framework of the international banking forum, is being prepared.
There we will make up our minds.
Also Anatoly Aksakov, stressing that "the chair does not hold," called a possible new head of the renewed Association "Russia" Georgi Luntovsky, who leaves the post of Deputy Chairman of the Central Bank in September, highly describing his business and human qualities.
