Andrey ohlopkov moved from the launch site
As it became known "Kommersant," the technical director of the launch site east Andrey ohlopkov began work in the State Space Research and Production Center (GKNPC) named after khronichev.
Previously, he was de facto involved in the construction of the Eastern launch site, but because of disagreements with the management of the land and space infrastructure Operation Centre (ECDIS), he was transferred to an enterprise in the Moscow fields, where he will coordinate production.
Mr. ohlopkov will not have a replacement: the post of technical director is likely to be abolished, and the functionality is spread across the divisions of ECDIS.
The top managers of several space industry enterprises, as well as an employee of the government apparatus, told about the fact that the technical director of the Eastern and Deputy Director General of ECDIS for technological development Andrey ohlopkov moved to work at the Khrunichev State Committee.
"He has been working in the new post for several weeks," - said the interlocutors "Kommersant" in the industry.
It was not possible to get an operational comment from ECDIS on Thursday, and Mr. ohlopkov himself was not available for comment.
However, the information "b" has been officially confirmed in the SCOC.
He decided to move to the position of director of production coordination, - said at the enterprise. - Andrey ohlopkov assigned to him the task of ensuring the launch minimum for the first launch at the launch site East fully fulfilled.
Mr. ohlopkov joined ECDIS in 2013, having served in space forces, in particular in Baikonur, and in plesecki - at the "northern" launch site he served as the First Deputy Commander in the rank of colonel.
In 2009, Andrei ohlopkov became the subject of a criminal case.
The investigation accused him of bribery: allegedly, from his submission, regional merchants received state orders for kickbacks, but did not fulfill their obligations to clean the separated parts of the launch vehicles in the Arkhangelsk region and the Republic of Komi.
He was found not guilty by a jury in 2012.
The technological development responsibilities assigned to it in ECDIS extended to different projects, but the main one was the construction of a launch site in the Far East.
Oleg Ostapenko, then head of the Federal Space Agency, said in an interview with Kommersant that the state of affairs in the East "was critical already in October 2013."
The fact is that a strategic mistake was made in the planning: the completion of the construction and the first launch of the Soyuz-2.1 launch vehicle were planned for the same time - the end of 2015.
In order to carry out the launch by the end of the year, it was decided to complete the construction six months earlier and the dates were shifted from December to July 2015.
In order to speed up the process, it was necessary to take a trick: ECDIS specialists began to conduct parallel installation of technological equipment on unfinished objects.
The main supporter of this idea was Andrei ohlopkov.
Despite the risks and still the transfer (instead of December 2015 "Soyuz" departed only on April 28, 2016), this idea justified itself, says the source "Kommersant" at the launch site: "Otherwise we would not carry out any launch from the east, but would be engaged in construction."
Deputy Prime Minister Dmitry Rogozin, who oversees the creation of the launch site, jokingly called Andrei ohlopkov his "cosmic Susanin," but it was from him almost always asked for information about the progress of the construction.
Mr. ohlopkov was remembered and straight: for example, in an interview with Kommersant, he proposed to deprive the Federal Agency for Special Construction (Special Construction) of the status of the only performer in Eastern and to work directly with subcontractors: "Why should we put all eggs in one basket of special system?"
This idea has found support in the government.
Since 2017, ECDIS has assumed the responsibilities of the general contractor to complete the construction and installation work at the start-up and technical complex by the planned fourth quarter.
