Red meat, dairy products and chocolate can help to ease the intake.
Red meat and chocolate is generally considered a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent research suggests otherwise: a diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products can help alleviate symptoms in those suffering from inflammatory bowel disease.
This incurable disease, which affects approximately 1.3 million people in the US and 300,000 in the UK, leads to Coles and abdominal bloating, chronic or bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Usually, to mitigate symptoms, patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy products, but researchers at the University of Washington have found that the main amino acid protein tryptophan promotes the production of immune cells that increase gut tolerance.
Lead researcher Dr. Marco column explained that immune cells in the gut make sure that harmful microbes coming with food do not penetrate the body.
Cells capable of triggering an inflammatory process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance, protecting the body while not harming sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too severely disturbed towards inflammation, it can lead to inflammatory bowel diseases.
Experiments have shown that mice with a certain bacterium in the gut appear to increase the tolerance of the cell.
And this bacteria needs tryptophan - one of the building elements of the protein - to trigger the emergence of these cells.
Professor column said: "We have established a link between one type of bacteria - lactobacco Illus reuteri - which is part of a normal gut microbiome, and the development of a population of cells that increase tolerance.
The more tryptophan was contained in the diet of mice, the more of these immune cells they had. "
He suggested that the same would work in humans: a combination of L. reuteri and a tryptophan-rich diet could contribute to a more tolerant and less inflammatory environment in the gut.
Postdoc Dr. Louise Cervantes-barraganvas, studying a variety of tolerance-enhancing immune cells, found that one group of experimental mice had these cells, and another group, which belonged to the same line but was kept separately, did not have them.
She suggested that the distinction could be caused by the gut microbiomes of mice - communities of bacteria, viruses and fungi that usually live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The DNA of the mice 'gut cells was sequencing, and six species of bacteria were found present in mice that have immune cells but are absent from mice that do not have them.
Mice grown in sterile environments that didn't have a good microbiome and didn't develop this kind of immune cells got L. reuteri, and they had immune cells.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in a liquid environment and then transferred small portions of fluid - without bacteria - to underdeveloped immune cells released from mice.
Immune cells have become tolerance-enhancing cells.
When the active component was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of tryptophan processing, known as indol-3-lactic acid.
When researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in mouse food, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when tryptophan levels were reduced by half, the number of cells also fell by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explains that humans have the same tolerance-enhancing cells as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether tryptophan by-products from L. reuteri contribute to cell development in humans in the same way as mice, but people suffering from inflammatory bowel diseases have been found to have defects in the genes associated with tryptophan.
She says: "Perhaps we need to strengthen the development of these cells, as inflammatory processes on the inner surface of the intestines depend on these cells.
High levels of tryptophan with L. reuteri could potentially lead to an expansion of their population. "
