Props for the White House cost taxpayers thousands of dollars
According to armed forces records provided to TIME magazine, the White House's decision last month to drive a Marine helicopter to the South Lawn for an event dedicated to American industrial production cost taxpayers as much as $24,000.
The white-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as "Marine One" when the president is on board, became the centerpiece of a July 17 White House event that showcased American construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and top White House officials examined technology products from all fifty states.
The Connecticut helicopter was displayed next to a Maine yacht, a Wisconsin fire truck and a Mississippi truck.
According to records from the first Marine Helicopter Squadron (HMX-1), the department responsible for managing the helicopter, the White House Military Department ordered the helicopter's presence in a private order, or "FRAGO," just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn on the occasion of the "unusual" event.
"I just wanted you to make sure that you are aware because this is an unusual widely publicized event," the HMX-1 commander wrote in an email to his chief, the Marine Corps' first deputy chief of aviation, on the eve of the event.
The letter indicated that the helicopter would arrive on the South Lawn at approximately 7 a.m. on July 17 to attend an event scheduled for 3 p.m. and would remain there until the lawn was released between 6 and 9 p.m. on the same day.
The letter adds that if departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required to return flight in accordance with working hours restrictions.
The first crew accompanied the helicopter during the event, and the unit's security officers remained close to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
It was not clear from the records obtained by TIME magazine whether the second crew was eventually required.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using public property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 clarified whether the event was contrary to this ruling.
"Among other things, we asked if it was a violation of the Hatch law, and we were told that it was not," the commander wrote.
"It looks like you have nowhere to go," the Deputy Chief replied.
The "Made in America" event was announced by the White House as an official event, and it was not covered by the hatchet law.
But even the official events have political notes.
During the event, the President made efforts to advance health care reform, then in development in the Senate, and praised attempts to regulate government regulations.
The use of aircraft known as "Marine One" and "Air Force One" for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are required to use them for travel.
But it is unusual to request them only in the interests of photography.
Trump was already the subject of discussions in February, when a presidential plane drove in the background during his first campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account is littered with messages complaining about his predecessor's use of the presidential plane.
"The White House is thrilled with the" Made in America "show, which featured products from 50 states made by American workers from American materials," said White House deputy press secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 crews often carry out training flights around the Washington metropolitan area and on the South Lawn to train the transportation of the President of the United States to the White House with the accuracy of an inch.
When Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 held 58 training landings outside the White House.
According to one of the officials, the flight made for the "Made in America" event was counted to the crew for the necessary training flights in a month.
The unit's helicopters also flew 11 additional hours that day as part of "non-presidential support tasks."
According to the White House, taxpayers were not charged for any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
A spokesman for Sikorsky said the company had not taken part in the South Lawn helicopter demonstration.
HMX-1 does not account for the budget for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But according to the Department of Defense's watch rates for the 2017 fiscal year, the Department of Defense's reimbursement rate for VH-3D is $24,380 per flight hour.
The unit's records recorded that the aircraft's time in the air was 30 minutes each way from its base airfield at the Marine Corps Air Base of kuantiko in Virginia.
The White House argues that the real cost of using the helicopter is much lower than this rate.
"It is completely wrong to calculate the cost to taxpayers based on the estimated reimbursement rate," Walters says.
"These indicative rates include personnel, services and many other irreversible costs that are included in the annual allocations."
According to a 2015 RAND study, reimbursement rates do not include the cost of personnel, but do take into account the cost of fuel, maintenance and costs specified in the contract.
At the time, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer defended the use of the helicopter for the event.
"The idea is to showcase this week things made in America," Spicer said.
"And I know that Sikorsky and Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to national security, and that there are, I assume, hundreds, if not thousands, of people whose workplace depends on it.
And I think, like most Americans, that we are all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment that so many Americans have worked tirelessly to build.
Therefore, of course, it is entirely appropriate to pay attention to this. "
It was unclear whether Trump had been interacting with the helicopter while inspecting the South Lawn during the event, but he sat exactly in the driver's seat in the fire vehicle.
Inside the White House, Trump addressed representatives of Sikorsky, joking with the press about his own fleet of company products.
"I know Sikorsky perfectly," the President said. "I have three of them."
