The National Union of unskilled, municipal and boiler workers (GMB) is concerned about investment in the McVitie's factory in Glasgow
The union is demanding guarantees from the managers of biscuit maker McVitie's over its long-term commitment to produce at the Glasgow plant.
The Scottish branch of GMB reports that the company has been silent on the issue of future investment at the Tolcross facility.
The factory, which produces, among other products, Hobnobs and Rich Tea cookies, employs more than 500 people.
Pladis, owner of McVitie's, says it has invested more than 5 million pounds in the facility over the past few years.
The company adds that in the event of any changes in the operation of the facility, employees and union representatives "will know about them first."
In a letter to the head of the company-owned facility, the GMB's Scottish branch demanded McVitie's reaction to the concern that funding would not be used to upgrade production lines.
Senior organiser Drew Duffy said: "Members of our Union are deeply concerned that we cannot get clarity from the general manager of the facility on business needs and the investment plan regarding the future of Tolcross."
Families have worked here for generations, and the concentration of workers is great in local society and in greater Glasgow; it is a crucial pillar of decent work in a territory of high unemployment and social deprivation.
So, in terms of jobs, wages and prosperity, and against the backdrop of Brexit, rising living standards and chronic decline in manufacturing, Glasgow's east end desperately needs to thrive manufacturing at McVitie's factory.
According to a spokesman for Pladis, "the head of the Tolcross facility only received a letter from the Scottish GMB branch yesterday, and the company will respond immediately, as we appreciate our continued cooperation with employees and union representatives."
Two months ago, we held a regular meeting with GMB staff and representatives in Tolcross, where we openly discussed a number of issues.
We talked to employees that as all companies operating in the most competitive and unstable economic climate, we are constantly reviewing our actions - and this applies to all our facilities and activities - in order to remain competitive.
"In recent years, we have invested more than 5 million pounds in our Tolcross facility, especially in production lines and improved performance."
We are fully aware of the value of Tolcross as a production facility, and in the event of any changes in work at this facility, employees and union representatives will learn about it first. "
