Did PSG warn Barcelona about Neymar's transition three years ago?
"La Liga" participant may regret his interest in Marco Verratti
Paris Saint-Germain will not stop chasing Neymar after the club offered 189 million pounds for his buyout, but did they warn Barcelona about the world record-setting raid held three years ago?
The sensational offer revived the summer transfer window when the Ligue 1 club were poised to break the world record for transition costs, more than double the previous mark associated with Paul Pogba's return to Manchester United last season for 89 million pounds.
When the transition is complete, Neymar will become the most expensive player in the world, as well as the highest paid professional athlete in the world, as PSG offers him a salary of more than 500,000 pounds a week clean.
It is known that Barcelona are furious at the way the offer was made, and how Neymar broke the contract, despite the fact that, as a source close to the Catalan club's management insists, the club has always done everything possible for the player since his transition from Santos in 2013.
But wasn't the football world warned about this possibility three years ago by the president of PSG?
When Manchester City expressed interest in hiring Blaise Matuidi in 2014, Nasser Al-Khelaifi issued a stern warning to any club that wanted to lure one of PSG's best players.
"I'm not worried because they know that if they touch one of our players, then we will oppose them, we will make offers to their players," Al-Khelaifi said.
"We respect all clubs.
But if they try to recruit one of our players, they are waiting for the consequences. "
Barcelona appeared to have crossed that line when the Spanish club expressed interest in PSG midfielder Marco Verratti earlier this summer.
PSG have made it clear that they will not release the Italian player of the national team on any terms, and now probably Barcelona are feeling the consequences of their offer in the form of the loss of one of their most valuable players, Neymar.
